Because the genetic diversity is low, and there is likely inbreeding among the extant population, the inbreeding mode for related is set to on. This in turn means the maximum likliehood estimators must be used. This makes calculations much slower, so estimators are not compared for combinations of larvae/adults or years.

Two of Each of the Three Years

2011 and 2012 Larval Relatedness

#read file in
df<-eltwlarvalPeeliSnps; main<-"2011 and 2012 Larval snps"
df<-df[-c(1:4),]
require(digest)
for (i in 1:length(df$X..2)) {
    df$unique[i] <- digest(df$X..2[i], algo = "xxhash32", seed = 1)
}
df <- cbind(df$unique, df)
names(df)[names(df) == "df$unique"] <- "allele"
df$unique <- NULL
df[1:10, c(1, 4)]

df2 <- df
df2[2:18] <- list(NULL)
df2 <- setNames(data.frame(t(df2[, -1])), df2[, 1])
rownames(df2) <- df2[, 1]
fishID <- df2[, 1]
df2[, 1] <- NULL
colnames(df2) <- paste("X", colnames(df2), sep = "")
df2 <- as.data.frame(apply(df2, 2, function(x) gsub("\\s+", "", x)))
indx <- sapply(df2, is.factor)
df2[indx] <- lapply(df2[indx], function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x)))
rm(indx)
x <- df2
library(data.table)
setDT(x)
for (j in seq_along(x)) {
    set(x, i = which(x[[j]] == 1 & !is.na(x[[j]])), j = j, value = j)
}
d1 <- data.frame(x)
rm(x)
rm(i)
rm(j)
d1.lst <- lapply(seq(1, ncol(d1), by = 2), function(x) {
    return(d1[, x:(x + 1)])
})
d1.lst.fil <- lapply(d1.lst, function(x) {
    x[, 1][!is.na(x[, 1]) & x[, 1] == "0"] <- x[, 2][!is.na(x[, 1]) & x[, 1] == "0"]
    x[, 2][!is.na(x[, 2]) & x[, 2] == "0"] <- x[, 1][!is.na(x[, 2]) & x[, 2] == "0"]
    return(x)
})
df2 <- do.call(cbind, d1.lst.fil)
rm(d1)
rm(d1.lst)
rm(d1.lst.fil)
df2 <- cbind(fishID, df2)
rownames(df2) <- df2[, 1]
df2[, 1] <- NULL
write.table(df2[, 1:800], "outRelated.txt", sep = " ", col.names = FALSE, row.names = TRUE, quote = FALSE)
require(related)
input <- readgenotypedata("outRelated.txt")
output <- coancestry(input$gdata, allow.inbreeding = TRUE, trioml = 1, wang = 1, lynchli = 1, lynchrd = 1, ritland = 1, quellergt = 1, dyadml = 1)

There are 2 alleles for each of these loci.

There are 107 individual fish in this set. From the simulations of known relationships we can choose cut off values for identifying relationships and colouring them in the plots. In this case FS or PO above 0.4; HS 0.1-0.4; unrelated fish have a relatedness value below 0.15.

require(igraph)
relData <- output$relatedness[, c(2, 3, 11)]
hist(relData[, 3], main = "Histogram of Milligan's   dyadic likelihood estimator")

lrelData <- relData
colnames(lrelData)[1] <- "from"
colnames(lrelData)[2] <- "to"
colnames(lrelData)[3] <- "weight"
lrelData$type <- "probRel"
relDataNoRows <- nrow(relData)
nrelData <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 4, nrow = relDataNoRows))
colnames(nrelData) <- c("id", "name", "type", "label")
nrelData[, 1] <- relData[, 2]
nrelData[, 2] <- relData[, 2]
newrow = c(relData[1, 1], relData[1, 1], NA, NA)
nrelData = rbind(nrelData, newrow)
nrow(nrelData)
## [1] 5672
length(unique(nrelData$id))
## [1] 107
nrow(lrelData)
## [1] 5671
nrow(unique(lrelData[, c("from", "to")]))
## [1] 5671
nrelData <- data.frame(unique(nrelData[, 1:4]))
tst <- ifelse(grepl("^A", nrelData$id), nrelData$type <- "adult", nrelData$type <- "larvae")
nrelData$type <- tst
rm(tst)
larvNrel <- merge(nrelData, larv, by.x = "id", by.y = "LarvalRecords_LarvaID")
larvNrel <- larvNrel[, c(1:4, 66)]
head(nrelData)

net <- graph_from_data_frame(d = lrelData, vertices = larvNrel, directed = FALSE)

Refine set and Plot relationships

#Limit to full siblings - this also makes it more sparse.
net.FS <- delete_edges(net, E(net)[weight<0.4])
l <- layout_with_fr(net.FS)

V(net.FS)$color=V(net.FS)$YearOnly #assign the "YearOnly" attribute as the vertex color
V(net.FS)$color=gsub("2011","indianred",V(net.FS)$color) #2011 will be red
V(net.FS)$color=gsub("2012","lightgoldenrod1",V(net.FS)$color) #2012 will be blue
V(net.FS)$color=gsub("2013","lightgreen",V(net.FS)$color) #2013 will be blue

E(net.FS)$weight<-E(net.FS)$weight*5

plot(net.FS, edge.arrow.size=0, edge.curved=0.2, vertex.size=5, vertex.color=V(net.FS)$color,vertex.frame.color="#555555",vertex.label=V(net)$name, vertex.label.color="black",vertex.label.cex=.7,edge.width=E(net.FS)$weight,layout=l)
#removed main=main;added edge.width=E(net.FS)$weight
title(main,cex.main=3)
legend(x=-1.5, y=-1.1, c("2011","2012", "2013"), pch=21,col="#777777", cex=.8, bty="n", ncol=1)
